Filament Feeder Tool is a simple wedge type tool to assist in maintenance of the Ultimaker2 filament feeder.  
The problem is that when you remove the filament feeder the filament drive motor shifts into the case resting on the motor cover.  This requires you to remove the motor cover and hold the motor while you reinstall the filament feeder.  This tool will allow you to complete the filament feeder removal and replacement without allowing the motor to shift its position.
In addition to this tool it is very helpful to have 2 40mm x 3mm cap screws.  
Initially remove just the top 2 screws from the filament feeder and replace them with the 40mm cap screws.  Once this is complete you can then remove the bottom 2 screws and insert the wedge keeper under the knurled pinion to hold the stepper motor in place.  Finally remove the top two long screws along with the filament feeder.  It is not necessary but suggested that one of the long screws is replaced to help keep the stepper motor aligned in the chance that the machine could get bumped and move the motor out of alignment.
Once the necessary maintenance is complete you remove the alignment screw and using the long screws insert them in the two top holes.  Then using these screws as handles remove the wedge tool and install the bottom two screws.  Finally replace the top long screws with the proper screws as original. 
You may find it beneficial to modify the thickness of the wedge tool to accommodate your units particular pinion to wall gap.

title: Cooling Fan Upgrade for Airbrush Compressor (for use in minimal spray cooling system)

description.text:
This design was developed for use in a minimal spray cooling system on my cnc machine. Airbrush compressors are relatively silent and keep neighbors friendly, but require aircooling to prevent overheating. See also http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1263973 Tested and working- but still a work in progress -> missing a voltage supply mount and links for daisychaining compressors in a double spray setup. The design allows for milling with a single 3mm mill and the the compressor stays so cool a 3D printable version would have been fine (tested to work over a continuous 2h session). The first iteration had a smaller fan which has since been replaced by the one seen in the first picture. Build instructions:
Aquire 1.5mm aluminum sheets. After milling the holes, rectangular areas may be milled down (by 0,75mm) for easy bending. Mill the outer contours and, after deburring, fold the sheet as depicted. Mount a fan using locknuts. The current working design uses a 12V 2,5 Watt PAPST Fan with 60mm x 60mm outer dimensions and 50x50 mm mounting points. The mount attaches firmly to the compressor via loosend screws from the compressor chamber/heatshield itself (these hold the compressor together).

description.text: This is a case for the Intel Edison / Grove / Arduino breakout board. It is intended to be used as a black box for projects. As such it is modular in design so that different modules can be designed and printed to hold different components without having to reprint the entire case and lid. I have included a module for the 2 line LCD component. I have also included a blank module that can be downloaded and customized. I have created a remixed LCD, Rotary Encoder & 2 Button module includes the LCD with a Rotary Encoder below it, flanked by 2 buttons. This would provide the basis for menu navigation or rudimentary input for various projects. Case v1 is the version pictured. In that version the analog pins are too close to the wall and are inaccessible without removing the breakout board. Case v2 strives to fix that by moving the hole pattern away from the wall. However, this results in the ports being quite recessed from their holes. A v3 may be forthcoming where a hole is cut in the side to access the analog pins. Feel free to remix this for that purpose. The screw holes in the lid are sized tightly to fit M3 screws. 16mm or shorter screws work well.

description.text: Era is a fast, cheap, simple, robust 3d printer design. This project is greatly inspired by Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer.

Era is designed with the principle: minimal efforts to achieve professional grade.： First, it is designed to be easily printable from any present printer. As most printers print in PLA or ABS, which are not as strong as metal or polycarbonate (the most common casing and part material on mid-to-hign end commercial printers), Era parts are designed to be very thick and stiff. They may not look fancy, but have a unified clean look, easy to print with minimal support, and is strong enough (sometimes over-strong that you may think it is wasting material, but the structural strength will pay in time) ,making it viberation-resilent and durable. Calibrate once and run everywhere! The second is the massive use of standard metal parts. Standard metals parts are stronger than plastic, robust, easy to get and cheap. Era features a fully printable compact dual Bowden printhead with adjustable height and cooling duct. It consists of only 1-peice printed part and mostly standard metal parts. Era also uses standard NEMA17 stepper instead of threaded rod NEMA17. All M3 T-nuts on Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer are changed to M4 T-nuts, as they are generally more common. The third is room for calibration. As low-priced materials often comes with low quality, there might be a lot of issues. Consider you ordered 2 pieces of aluminum extrusion in 308mm, but got one in 307mm and one in 309mm, and they cannot fit on the opposite sides of a square! You ordered two "exactly same hotends", only to find they are different in height and cannot be installed together! Era takes full consider of these problems and leaves room for calibration. With careful adjustments on some screws, you can get a perfectly calibrated printer even with low-quality materials. And "minimal efforts" is not only for users, but also developers. All Era parts are drawn from scratch in OpenSCAD, so a lot of code can be reused and easily modified. It's also very easy to read and understand. Join the development of Era at https://github.com/sgsdxzy/era and make Era better! Or you can even use the established Era code base to build your own 3D printer!
We desgin for a minimum of 200mm/s. 400mm/s is possible.
It should cost around 1200-1400 CNY (around 200 USD) If you live in China and buy all parts online.
We use a minimum number of printed/non-standard parts in favor of standard parts.
It should run 7/24 if you give a good supply of filament and power.

description.text:
Need a dipole support? Here's one! This one is designed to slide down the top of a telescoping fiberglass pole mast about 1.5 ft for HF inverted Vee use but also works for tape measure dipoles if you loop the coax through the hole instead. 
It's great!
Print it any way you like. This part isn't exactly rocket science.
mathematically extruded

I wanted to print using 1.75 mm filament because I had a lot of filament in that size. I designed these parts to assist in that endeavour. There are 7 parts in this print but really only 4 are useful and only 2 are essential. Included you will find a .pdf that better explains how to implement the 1.75 pathway. The Collet clip is redundant unless you break or loose one. This one is pretty much identical but you could use the source and make it as thin or thick as you desire. The Bowden tube / liner I found on ebay was 4mm OD 2mm ID TFE and it works great.
The Outside tube that I line with this TFE tube is 1/4 ID Polyethylene Tubing I got at a hardware. I drilled out the TFE Hot End isolator so the Liner goes all the way through to the Olson Block. At the hot end I take 2mm ID stainless tubing that I purchased on ebay. This liner tubing is tapered at the extruder end to fit snugly at the tip end of the nozzle. The other end is chamfered to let the filament find the opening easily. This adapter tube goes all the way into the TFE Hot End isolator and meets the TFE liner inside there. By cutting the TFE liner a bit long (1/2 to 3/4 inch) (or (13 to 19mm) and using some pressure when installing the Bowden tube into the Filament Feeder. I find that this secures the liner to the top of the stainless steel hot end liner and makes a complete 1.75 mm compatible pathway for the filament even when there is some resistance due to pressure (like a clog). In spite of that it might be good to make a small mark on the liner just at the extruder end so you can visually see if the liner tube is being pushed up due to excessive pressure. What I really want is to be able to print a working Collet that is optimized in size and design to bite the 4mm OD TFE tubing directly. This will eliminate the pre-loading of the Bowden tube and will just be simpler. About the Collet you see in this print: The Collet I designed is currently a work in progress and I have not had any success in making the first one that will work. Nylon is on order and when I succeed it will be in this mix. What I have had is some success in learning how to embed the required metal components into the print. As you see in this print one component is a cut out template that I use to drill metal from a tin can and then use a high speed cutting wheel to cut the outside perimeter as per this template.

This does not mean it does not work by adding tension to liner against the Bowden tube that method yelds me more than 200 hours between cleaning the extruder. The upper filament adapter is the little cube.  The two notches in this cube accommodate the reinforcements inside the stock Ultimaker Filament Feeder.  This part is essential to provide a limit stop for the 2mm id TFE Bowden tube.
The lower filament adapter replaces the metal feral and inserts up through the pinch wheel housing.  This guides the 1.75 filament keeping it oriented  properly to be pinched between the idler bearing and the knurled pinion on the feeder stepper motor shaft.

title: Modified Pegboard Spool Holder With Pegboard Bracket Spacers

description.text:
I'm not one to give up easily, so after printing the original spool holder and finding out that it didn't quite work I set about fixing it. I didn't like the idea of reprinting the entire dowel so looked around in my fixings and found four M6x20mm cap headed machine screws.
Using the dimensions of these screws I then designed an extension piece for each end. Simply making a small extension that made up for the 8.9mm (0.345") that the dowel lacked in length would not have had any strength so it had to be longer, meaning the pegboard bracket would have to be moved over by an inch, adding half an inch (12.7mm) to each extension piece. This would also allow me to use my large spools which originally would've been too wide for this design. I decided to extend the pegs that sat on the brackets to 18mm as they were rather small and didn't use the entire width of the bracket. Holes for the screws were added so that they would pass through and the caps would sit just below the surface when screwed in. A recess for the existing peg was added to the rear side.
The extensions were printed using a large (10mm) raft margin to ensure they were stable when printing the large peg and supports were used to ensure that the recess was formed correctly, otherwise fitting would be a nightmare. When complete the holes for the bolts were reamed out using a 6mm drill bit and the support material removed from the recess with a screwdriver (it's actually far easier than it may look). The extension pieces were fitted to the end, the original dowel was drilled to approx. 6mm using a 5mm drill bit and tapped to M6. The original dowel was printed in PLA, at 25% infill using the fast diamond pattern and took the tapping quite well. Some sanding was required on the original dowel to fit snugly but finally the parts were bolted together.
I understand that this modification requires quite a bit of additional work, tools and hardware but I was fortunate enough to have this and maybe it can help someone else out too.

Since my pegboard it made from stamped sheet metal it is rather thin, so originally the pegs on the brackets were too far back and the bracket just hung down. I measured the gap and designed a spacer, taking in to account the 1mm double-sided tape I would use to fix it. the resulting blocks are perfect and the brackets now sit square and support the spool properly.

  • Remove support material from recess
  • Ream holes using a drill bit (I mounted mine in a vice and turned the part around it by hand, don't drill while holding the part).
  • Fit over existing dowel, sand as necessary for a close fit.

description.text: Here's a little something you may want to print before you need it.  Luckily, I upgraded to the XYZ Pro so I had another printer to fix the broken machine. The circles had drifted out of round to an annoying degree so I went to tighten the belts only to find that one of my belts adjustments was maxed out.  Upon closer inspection, I found that one of the plastic cup that holds the shaft bearings for the Y axis drive system was broken into several pieces.  Upon disassembly, the other one cracked as well (see them both in the picture).  They were both very brittle.  I see in the new machine they are made from a different material so I have to assume this was a problem.  This is a replacement pice for that which is broken.  I created two version.  One with tabs for the tension springs (which were not broken so I didn't replace them) and another for the motor side where I replaced them both.  Perfect fit first time :-) and an hour later my printer is happy again in that whole EMO sort of way....

This is angry_monk's dial calipers.
Taken from his "in pieces" .stl files, split apart as needed, and recombined into a single-plate file suitable for output to a regular FDM printer.

Notes: If printing with ABS, you must have a fan pointing at the extrusion target. In my case, that consisted of a fan shroud/duct [ http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:989420 ], fastened around my extruder's cold end heat sink.
  • Hot end temperature: 235°C
  • Bed temperature: 110°C

Some minor sanding of surfaces and slight reaming out of a couple of holes is about all I needed to do to fit everything together, and a few drops of superglue to make it permanent.  
However, despite adding a little bit of light grease, the gear ratio between the rack and the final drive gear on the needle is too high to allow for the overall "slop" between the gears.
The calipers can only safely be opened/closed by either rotating the big gear left of the dial (which will cause the needle to skip teeth), or spinning the needle.  It is possible to take a precision measurement by spinning the needle to open/close it.
All resizing and plating done in Slic3r.  Black marks expertly added and needle "painted" with a sharpie. ;-)

description.text: I have printed the fuselage and tailplane and am currently printing the wings.  Instead of Carbon Fiber, I've been using lightweight brass or aluminum tubing (enlarging holes as necessary on my drill press).  Overall, the design is super sturdy and I plan to put in an ArduPilot system on board (I also put in a more powerful motor and a 3 bladed prop (couldn't find what was specified, but found the equivalent in the US).  One thing that bugs me is the landing on belly as I don't have a prop with folding blades, so instead I need legs.  For a nose strut you can bend up a torsion spring leg from hanger wire.  I put in a slot to place a piece of bent wire to support the leg.  I recommend printing these as they are, on their side so that the bending lines are in the direction of lift (up and down).  The wire should absorb most of the impact.  For all of us in the US, 2" wheels will be fine (in my case, that clears the prop from the ground).  I don't expect it to take off on its gear, but at least when it hits the ground, the prop will be protected (a little).  You'll have to position the gear based on your own build, but I will have it in section 3 just about at the trailing edge of the wing due to Weight and Balance.  This is as yet untested, so caveat emptor, but it's a start.  One note: as you can see, the groove for the embedded wire goes through the wheel axle: obviously, you don't nee the wire to go that far down, but if you glue in piece below the axle hole, countersink your axle screw, that does the job.  What I will do is enlarge the hole and use a larger screw, drilling a hole THROUGH the screw which allows the wire to be continuous.  This will make everything that much more rigid.
